on
to
the
brink
of
the
grave,
and
dissolution
flings
us
in
a
rag
eaten
through
and
through
with
disease,
wrung
together
with
pain,
stamped
into
the
churchyard
sod
by
the
inexorable
heel
of
despair.
But
the
man
of
regular
life
and
rational
mind
never
despairs.
He
loses
his
property
it
is
a
blow
he
staggers
a
moment;
then,
his
energies,
roused
by
the
smart,
are
at
work
to
seek
a
