her
hand
to
court
my
hand;
I
felt
it
was
made
to
nestle
in
mine;
I
could
not
relinquish
my
right
to
it,
nor
could
I
withdraw
my
eyes
for
ever
from
hers,
where
I
saw
so
much
happiness,
such
a
correspondence
of
heart
with
heart;
over
whose
expression
I
had
such
influence;
where
I
could
kindle
bliss,
infuse
awe,
stir
deep
delight,
rouse
sparkling
spirit,
and
sometimes
waken
pleasurable
dread.
My
hopes
to
will
and
possess,
my
resolutions
to
merit
and
rise,
rose
in
array
against
me;
and
here
I
was
about
to
plunge
into
the
gulf
of
absolute
destitution;
"and
all
this,"
suggested
an
inward
