there
was
a
chink
in
my
cavernous
cell;
for,
eventually,
I
saw,
or
seemed
to
see,
a
ray
pallid,
indeed,
and
cold,
and
doubtful,
but
still
a
ray,
for
it
showed
that
narrow
path
which
conscience
had
promised
after
two,
three
hours'
torturing
research
in
brain
and
memory,
I
disinterred
certain
remains
of
circumstances,
and
conceived
a
hope
that
by
putting
them
together
an
expedient
might
be
framed,
and
a
resource
discovered.
The
circumstances
were
briefly
these:
Some
three
months
ago
M.
Pelet
had,
on
the
occasion
of
his
fete,
given
the
boys
a
treat,
which
treat
consisted
in
a
party
of
pleasure
to
a
certain
place
of
public
