out
of
which
he
will
come
(I
trust)
a
wiser
and
a
better
man.
I
see
him
now;
he
stands
by
Hunsden,
who
is
seated
on
the
lawn
under
the
beech;
Hunsden's
hand
rests
on
the
boy's
collar,
and
he
is
instilling
God
knows
what
principles
into
his
ear.
Victor
looks
well
just
now,
for
he
listens
with
a
sort
of
smiling
interest;
he
never
looks
so
like
his
mother
as
when
he
smiles
pity
the
sunshine
breaks
out
so
